Hey there! This problem looks like a classic application of completing the square.  

First, let's rewrite the expression in a way that makes it easier to work with. We can think of it as a quadratic form:

$$
\begin{pmatrix} x & y & z \end{pmatrix} 
\begin{pmatrix} 2 & -1 & 0 \\ -1 & 2 & -2 \\ 0 & -2 & 5 \end{pmatrix} 
\begin{pmatrix} x \\ y \\ z \end{pmatrix} 
+ \begin{pmatrix} -4 & 0 & -2 \end{pmatrix} 
\begin{pmatrix} x \\ y \\ z \end{pmatrix} + 15
$$

Now, the key is to diagonalize that matrix in the middle. This will let us rewrite the quadratic part in terms of squares. Then, we'll complete the square for the linear terms. Once we've done that, the minimum value will be easy to spot!

